## üéº **Music Theory Method: The Ear Training Corruption**

In music education, there's a concept called "ear training"‚Äîdeveloping the ability to hear and identify musical elements. Good ear training helps you internalize the relationship between what you hear and what you understand. But there's a danger: if you train your ear exclusively on certain types of music, you lose the ability to hear other types as coherent. Classical musicians sometimes struggle to hear jazz harmony. Pop-trained ears can find atonal music incomprehensible.

The four warning signs represent a kind of corrupted ear training for value recognition:

"I should pay for Premium to grow faster" means you've been trained to hear "growth" as a resolution, a satisfying harmonic movement. Your ear for what constitutes progress has been tuned to recognize only increasing numbers as "success."

"I need to post more to keep engagement up" means you can no longer hear the rhythm of your own creative process. You're following an externally imposed tempo, like a musician who's lost the ability to play without a metronome and now thinks the clicks are the music.

"My follower count defines my success" means you've been trained to hear only one frequency. It's like having perfect pitch for middle C but being tone-deaf to everything else. You can precisely identify that one note (the metric) but you've lost the ability to hear the full symphony of your creative life.

"I wonder how much I could earn from monetization" means you're trying to hear monetary value in every creative phrase, like a musician who can only hear music in terms of its commercial potential rather than its aesthetic qualities.

The insidious part about ear training is that once your ear is trained a certain way, other sounds don't just seem wrong‚Äîthey seem like nothing at all. If you've lost the ability to hear certain intervals or chord progressions, they don't register as music. Similarly, once your value-recognition has been trained on follower count, work that doesn't generate followers doesn't register as valuable. It becomes inaudible.

The EJECT response is recognizing that your ear has been corrupted and you need retraining. But here's the challenge: you can't retrain your ear by listening to the same music. You need exposure to different sounds, different rhythms, different ways of organizing value. You need to deliberately practice hearing things that the platform has trained you to ignore‚Äîthe quality of a single deep conversation, the satisfaction of solving a hard problem regardless of who sees it, the feeling of improving your craft even when no one notices.

The metric-not-mirror principle is understanding that the metric is one note in a complex chord, not the entire tonal center. Your ear has been trained to resolve everything back to that one note, to hear it as "home." But actually, there are many possible tonal centers, many ways to resolve creative tension that don't involve follower count at all.

